\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b cephalonicus} (C. Presl) Ascherson & Graebner,{\i   Syn. Mitteleur. Fl. }{\b 6}({\b 2}): 779 (1909): More or less caespitose. Leaflets 6-7 pairs, usually densely hairy on both surfaces. Bracts ovate-lanceolate, with prominent, anastomosing lateral veins. Corolla whitish, rarely pale purplish; standard c. 1½ times as long as calyx. {\i  Greece}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b c}) Subsp. {\b muticus} (Pau) Rivas Goday & Borja, {\i  Anal. Inst. Bot. Cavanilles}{\b  19}: 406 (1961): Caespitose. Leaflets 6-7 pairs, usually obtuse, densely appressed-hairy on both surfaces. Bracts lanceolate, with weak lateral veins. Corolla pale purplish or yellow; standard about equalling calyx. •{\i   E.C. Spain.} 
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b d}) Subsp. {\b nevadensis} (Boiss.) P. Monts.,{\i   Collect. Bot.} ({\i  Barcelona}) {\b 2}: 266 (1949): Caespitose. Leaflets 6-7 pairs, acute, densely appressed-hairy on both surfaces. Bracts linear-lanceolate, with a single, central vein. Corolla purple; standard about equalling calyx. •{\i   S. Spain}.
\par

