\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 77. A. angustifolius} Lam., {\i  Encycl. Méth. Bot.}{\b  1}: 321 (1783). Caespitose, forming dense tussocks, spiny; stems 5-20 cm, woody at base. Leaves 2·5-6 cm, the spine-like rhachis slender, leaflets 6-10 pairs, 2-7 × 0·75-2 mm, narrowly elliptical to linear, acute or subobtuse, usually densely appressed-hairy on both surfaces; stipules glabrous or hairy. Peduncles very short or up to slightly longer than leaves; racemes ovoid, with 3-12 flowers; bracts 4-8 mm, linear-lanceolate. Calyx 5-9 mm, appressed-hairy, the teeth ¼-½ as long as tube. Corolla white; standard 13-23 mm; wings 10-20 mm; keel 8-15 mm, sometimes purplish. Legume 10-15 mm, exceeding calyx, oblong-lanceolate, triquetrous, with short, dense, appressed hairs. •{\i   Mountain rocks. Balkan peninsula, Thasos, Kriti}. Al Bu Cr Gr Ju.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Two subspecies may be recognized. There is also clinal variation in certain characters, particularly in the length of the calyx teeth, which decreases towards the south.
